node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text:
Photo by @carltonward / Roseate spoonbills take flight at Audubon's Florida Coastal Islands Sanctuary, in Tampa Bay. The roseate spoonbill is characterized by pink feathers and a spoon-shaped bill, used for foraging in shallow wetlands and bays. With conservation measures, state populations have rebounded from a low of 15 pairs in 1935. Tampa Bay is now home to nearly 15% of spoonbills living in Florida, though loss of wetland and mangrove habitat still threatens their survival. 
 
To learn more, please follow me @CarltonWard and @PathofthePanther. The Path of the Panther project is supported by the National Geographic Society to inspire protection of the Florida Wildlife Corridor. @insidenatgeo @fl_wildcorridor @audubon_fl @audubonsociety #KeepFLWild

node.text: Photo by @acacia.johnson / A boy pulls a toy snowmobile over the sea ice near Arctic Bay, in Canada's Nunavut region, on a break during a nine-hour snowmobile trip to a fishing lake. Every year, the Inuit community of Arctic Bay—called Ikpiarjuk in Inuktitut—holds an ice fishing derby for arctic char over a holiday weekend in May. Families and friends travel by snowmobile to spend three days camped together around frozen lakes, teaching their children to fish and enjoying time together. Follow me at @acacia.johnson for more stories from the Arctic and beyond. #nunavut #arcticbay #ikpiarjuk #baffinisland #seaice

node.text: Photo by Luján Agusti @lujanag / Sierra Madre, Mexico: Detail of the sandals worn by a member of the Rarámuri (Tarahumara) people in the community of Rojochique. This type of footwear, common among women and men here, is used for walking several kilometers and even for running. The Rarámuri live in remote settlements in rocky canyons, so it's easier to travel between communities on foot rather than in a vehicle or on the back of an animal. Follow me at @lujanag to learn more about this and other stories.

node.text:
Photos by Danielle Villasana @davillasana / Between the dangerous circumstances that pushed them out of their home country and their traumatic journeys north, Kataleya Nativi Baca and Alexa Smith faced unthinkable challenges. Both transgender women, they fled Honduras due to violence and threats. “I told my mom: it’s better if I had just died so as not to live the life I lived of them not accepting me,” said Kataleya of her family. Her brother beat her, fracturing her collarbone. 

Despite life-threatening situations and setbacks in the asylum process due to closed borders from the pandemic, they crossed documented into the United States this year. “I was happy to see the United States' flag,” said Kataleya.

To learn more about women migrating around the globe, explore a group project by National Geographic and the Everyday Projects (@everydayeverywhere), which is also being featured at @Photoville. Follow me @davillasana for more images on human rights issues worldwide. Many thanks to @insidenatgeo for their support of this work. #everydayeverywhere #women #migration #photoville

Photo by Karine Aigner @kaigner / The corn snake (Pantherophis guttatus) is a nonvenomous rat snake species, and one of the most popular reptile pets in the world. While corn snakes can bite, they're quite docile in personality. As constrictors, they strike their prey to gain a hold on it, and then wrap their bodies around it, squeezing out the life. Each individual has its own pattern and color—some more colorful and stunning than others. 

This one was not a pet. It lay spread out on the tar road in front of my car, soaking in the warmth on an overcast day. Any day meeting a snake is a good day in my world! For more stories on wildlife-human interactions, follow me at @kaigner. #snake #ratsnake #reptiles

Photo by @nataliekeyssar |  On July 4, teams in a women's rodeo—called charreada, from the Mexican tradition—competed in a regional semifinal event in Snelling, California. This team—the Flor de Gardenia Escaramuza—performs an albanico, or fan maneuver, riding in perfect unison at a gallop. 

Teams of eight riders do complex synchronized choreography while riding sidesaddle in Adelitas outfits, inspired by the garb of the women who fought in the Mexican Revolution. The sport now is widely practiced in the U.S. among vibrant Chicano communities, where women can celebrate their horsemanship and their heritage—and compete for a chance to participate in finals in Mexico. Photo by @waynelawrence / Nancy Luehman, whose mother passed away from COVID-19, is a volunteer for the “In America: Remember” project, placing thousands of flags in each of her shifts on the National Mall in Washington, D.C. Artist Suzanne Brennan Firstenberg is behind the installation (and a previous one last fall near the city's RFK Stadium), where over 670,000 white flags will honor each individual lost to the virus. It's the largest such exhibition on the mall since the presentation of the AIDS Memorial Quilt, in 1987. 

White benches placed throughout the exhibit's 3.8 miles of walking paths allow visitors to pause in quiet reflection. The display will remain up through October 3. The public is invited to dedicate flags for loved ones, and virtual tributes are possible through InAmericaFlags.org, where volunteers will fulfill the requests, inscribing and planting flags.  For more on this story, click the link in our bio.

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / Meet Horst Fankhauser, a legend in Austrian mountaineering. He has climbed 8,000-meter peaks in the Himalaya with Reinhold Messner, and has been the warden at Franz-Senn Hütte for over 30 years. Now Horst fears for his beloved landscape. In the last 10 years or so, the glaciers surrounding his home, the Stubai Alps in Tirol, have dramatically changed. The rate at which they are melting away is getting faster. In this photograph, Horst is standing in the same place that the 1930s photograph he's holding was taken. “You do not only see the change, you feel it. It hurts,” Horst says. If we continue on our present course, our grandchildren will most likely know glaciers only from postcards like this one.
